## Autonomy axis (qualitative)

This is the axis that does not move. We score each tool on three dimensions:

- **Runs on user infra?** — can the user run it without phoning home?
- **Open core?** — is the retrieval/storage path open-source end-to-end?
- **Vendor lock-in score** — 1 (none) to 5 (complete). High = data, format,
  and operations are tied to one vendor.

| Tool | Runs on user infra? | Open core? | Lock-in score |
|---|---|---|---:|
| **nox-mem** | yes (sqlite + sqlite-vec, single binary) | yes (MIT) | **1** |
| agentmemory | yes — *but requires proprietary `iii-engine` daemon* | partial | 3 |
| Memanto | no (SaaS only — Moorcheh) | no | 5 |
| mem0 | yes (PostgreSQL + Qdrant) | yes (Apache 2.0) | 2 |
| Letta / MemGPT | yes (PostgreSQL + optional Qdrant) | yes (Apache 2.0) | 2 |
| Zep | yes (Zep Open Source) / SaaS Pro tier | yes (Apache 2.0) | 2 |
| built-in `MEMORY.md` | yes (filesystem only) | n/a | 1 |

> The autonomy axis is **fixed by design**, not measured. It is also the
> only axis where nox-mem has a structural moat — the benchmark numbers can
> wobble, but the architectural choice "no daemon, no SaaS, no cloud" is
> stable.

